In .NET MAUI, use the `App` lifecycle events combined with `Preferences` for lightweight draft persistence.

**In `App.xaml.cs`** — hook the platform lifecycle events:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            page.SaveDraft();
    };

    window.Activated += (s, e) =>
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            page.RestoreDraft();
    };

    return window;
}
```

**In `NotePage.xaml.cs`** — save/restore using `Preferences`:

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "NoteDraft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    public void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Preferences.ContainsKey(DraftKey))
            NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Call this when the user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app goes to background — save here.
- **`Window.Activated`** fires on resume — restore here.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text; for large drafts, use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with file I/O instead.
- Call `ClearDraft()` when the user intentionally saves or discards the note so stale drafts don't reappear.
